3.11.24  9:57 pm   in search for peace by mccoy tyner, he plays a chord with D in the bass, C, F, Bb in the middle, and Eb in the melody. it doesn't feel like an inversion of a Bb chord at all though. and in fact it sounds bad if you put the F too close to the bass, it doesn't work as well because it starts to sound like Bbmaj7add9 or Dmin7, whereas if you add a F# near the bass instead it sounds really cool (but omitting the F# makes it sound more relaxed and airy). meaning that using conventional notation this would maybe be called 'D7#5#9no3', and maybe even throw a b9 and b5 in there as well because the Bb turns into an Ab after a second. but this is super long and messy, so i propose we call this D☮, pronounced D-peace. what do you think of the chord?

      sounds like actually a fairly normal rendition of what would probably appear on paper as D7alt, in this context. and i'm pretty sure the F# note actually is in there

3.11.24  7:24 pm   How come you repeat 7 and skip 1 in "9 8 7"?

      the 7 just picks up where the previous line left off, and the 1 is not skipped, it's heavily featured in many different ways. in the "i wonder" section, it can be heard at the beginning of every line if you listen closely. but if that's not enough, it says "i wonder if you wonder what number we're counting to". according to the downward trajectory, it could be blindingly obvious that we've been counting toward 1. but if that's not enough, there's another counting section later in the song which includes 1 outright
